      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":333,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":333,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very relaxed, just getting the legs moving. No pressure on pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":333,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable easy pace. Conversational effort throughout — you should be able to speak in full sentences.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace, gentle finish. Short mobility routine afterwards recommended.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes very easy jogging to loosen up. A few dynamic leg swings and hip circles if time allows.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 minutes easy jog, then 5–10 minutes of light stretching focusing on calves, hamstrings, and hip flexors.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This run builds your aerobic base — the foundation everything else sits on. Running 75–80% of your weekly volume at easy pace is central to Daniels' approach and protects you from accumulating too much fatigue early in the block. Keep the effort genuinely easy; if in doubt, slow down. Your easy pace range is 5:08–5:53/km, so aim for the middle of that band today.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Cruise Intervals at Threshold\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":65,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":333,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":256,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":333,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jogging warmup. By the end of the warmup you should feel loose and ready to run harder.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":256,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First threshold cruise interval. Comfortably hard — you can speak a few words but not a full sentence. Threshold pace is 4:16/km.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":333,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy recovery jog between intervals. Recover enough to hit the next rep at quality pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":256,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second cruise interval. Maintain form — relaxed shoulders, tall posture, quick cadence.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":333,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":256,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third cruise interval. This is the hardest one mentally — stay focused and trust your fitness.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":333,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy cooldown jog. Let the heart rate come back down gradually.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy running. Include 4–6 strides (20-second accelerations) in the final 5 minutes of the warmup to prime the legs.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging followed by dynamic stretching and foam rolling if available.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Threshold work raises your lactate threshold — the pace you can sustain before lactic acid accumulates faster than you can clear it. For your 3:15 marathon goal, a strong threshold is critical. Three 8-minute cruise intervals with 2-minute easy recoveries is a classic Daniels prescription. The key here is consistency across all three reps — not positive splitting. If the third rep feels dramatically harder, ease off a touch on rep one next time.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":348,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":348,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Very gentle start.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":348,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy aerobic run at the comfortable end of your easy range (5:28–5:53/km). This run is about active recovery and keeping the aerobic engine ticking. Resist any urge to push.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Wind down gently.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes of very easy jogging, no rush.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 minutes easy, then spend a few minutes on hip flexor and calf stretches.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This run sits between your threshold session and your long run. Its job is to keep blood flowing through the legs and clear any residual fatigue without creating new stress. The temptation on a Friday is to run at a 'normal' easy pace, but consider erring toward the slower end of your easy band (5:40–5:53/km) so you arrive at Sunday's long run fresh.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Run with Marathon Pace Finish\",\"target_distance_km\":26,\"target_duration_minutes\":140,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":333,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":272,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very conservatively. The first 10 minutes should feel almost too easy.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":90,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":333,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady easy long run effort. Stay in the 5:08–5:30/km range. Focus on time on feet, not pace. Fuel every 30–45 minutes with gels or real food, and hydrate regularly.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":272,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 30 minutes at marathon goal pace (4:32/km). This teaches your body and mind what race pace feels like on tired legs — one of the most race-specific adaptations you can build. It should feel hard but controlled.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog to finish. Do not stop abruptly — let the heart rate ease down.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin very easy. Spend the first kilometre almost walking pace if needed. Your body will warm up naturally over the first 15–20 minutes.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"10 minutes easy jogging, then a thorough stretching session — 10–15 minutes covering all major muscle groups. Prioritise nutrition and hydration in the 30 minutes after finishing.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is your most important weekly session for marathon preparation. The early easy portion builds aerobic capacity, fat oxidation, and muscular endurance. The marathon-pace finish (final 30 minutes at 4:32/km) is one of the most powerful tools in marathon training — it teaches your neuromuscular system to hold race pace when fatigued, which is exactly what race day demands. This week we hold 26 km to match your recent long run, building familiarity before we progress. Nutrition practice during this run is non-negotiable — race day fuelling strategy should be rehearsed here every single week.\",\"perceived_effort\":7}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
